  issn = {0022-3077},
  abstract = {1. Recent results have shown that nucleus ventralis posterior lateralis pars oralis (VPLo) of the thalamus receives short-latency sensory input from the periphery and projects to the motor cortex. There are grounds for believing that sensory information may reach VPLo via the dorsal column nuclei. We set out to test this hypothesis using neuroanatomical tracing methods. 2. Injections of tritiated amino acids into the dorsal column nuclei did not lead to autoradiographic labeling of terminal ramifications in nucleus VPLo, but such labeling was present in nucleus ventralis posterior lateralis pars caudalis (VPLc). 3. Small injections of horseradish peroxidase (HRP) were made into VPLo or into adjacent nuclei. The sites of injection were determined from the distribution of short-latency field potentials evoked by electrically stimulating the contralteral median and ulnar nerves. Injections into VPLo and VLc led to retrograde labeling of cells in the deep cerebellar nuclei, but not in the dorsal column nuclei. For reasons discussed in the text, it is unlikely that the cerebellar nuclei relay sensory information at short latency to the thalamus and motor cortex. Injections of HRP into VPLo also led to labeling of cells in several laminae of the spinal cord. 4. Cells of the cuneate and external cuneate nuclei, including presumed group I muscle afferent relay, were labeled only when injections spread into VPLc. Such injections were also accompanied by retrograde labeling of cells in the vestibular nuclei. 5. HRP injections of VPLo retrogradely labeled corticothalamic cells only in area 4; injections of VPLc labeled corticothalamic cells in areas 3, 1, and 2 of sensory cortex. Injections at the border between VPLo and VPLc did not preferentially label corticothalamic cells in area 3a of the cortex. There is no evidence from this finding or from other studies for a separate anatomically distinct thalamic relay to an area 3a. 6. Injections that were confined to nucleus VLo retrogradely labeled cells only in the globus pallidus. 7. The origin of the short-latency sensory input to VPLo is still unclear.},
